nodes.title: Width and Height Info
widgets_values:
Default and best settings: 1024w x 576h

You can experiment. I was able to get results at 1024x1024.

nodes.title: Video Frames Info
widgets_values:
Length of the Video. Example 24 frames at 12 fps = 2 sec movie.

Default for SVD_XT: 25

Default for SVD: 14

Best not to change this setting.

nodes.title: Augmentation Level Info
widgets_values:
This will dictate the amount of life given to objects in your video.

Lower values means less life.
Higher values means more life.

Stick between 0 - .5 if you're new.

nodes.title: FPS_ID Info
widgets_values:
This will dictate the speed and quality of objects in the video. This is not FPS though. 

Lower values means movements will be faster with less detail
Higher values means movements will be slower with more detail

Stick between 1 - 12 if you're new.

nodes.title: Motion_Bucket_ID Info
widgets_values:
This will dictate the amount of movement in your video.

Lower values means less movement. 1 equals no movement.
Higher values means more movement. 537 is max.

Stick between 10 - 100 if you're new.

nodes.title: Steps Info
widgets_values:
This will dictate the level of quality of each individual frame.

Lower values means less quality. Faster Rendering
Higher values means higher quality. Slower Rendering

Stick between 25 - 30 if you're new.

nodes.title: CFG Info
widgets_values:
This will dictate the sharpness of each individual frame.

Lower values means less sharpness.
Higher values means higher sharpness.Too much and it will look baked.

Stick between 2 - 3 if you're new.

nodes.title: CFG Info
widgets_values:
Denoising is a post-processing step that attempts to smooth out these variations while preserving the important features of the image.

Lower values means less denoising.
Higher values means higher denoising.

Stick between 0 - 3 if you're new.

nodes.title: clear_cache_after_n_frames Info
widgets_values:
This parameter might control how long the model retains information in its cache. Video processing often involves working with a certain number of frames at a time, and clearing the cache after a certain number of frames could be a strategy to manage memory usage or ensure that the model is processing the most relevant and recent information.

Higher retains more frame data, might get better results. Better if you have HighVRAM
Lower retains less frame data, faster results. Better if you have LowVRAM.

nodes.title: multiplier Info
widgets_values:
Adjusts the impact or influence of smoothness of video.

Higher value more smooth.
Less value less smooth.

Stick to 2 - 3 if you're new.

nodes.title: Alpha_matting_foreground_threshold Info
widgets_values:
foreground threshold is a value or criterion used to distinguish between what is considered the foreground and what is considered the background. This threshold helps determine which pixels are likely part of the foreground and which are part of the background.

For example, a higher threshold might be more conservative, considering only pixels that are confidently foreground, while a lower threshold might be more inclusive, potentially including more pixels in the foreground region.

nodes.title: Alpha_matting_background_threshold Info
widgets_values:
background threshold is a value or criterion used to distinguish between what is considered the foreground and what is considered the background. This threshold helps determine which pixels are likely part of the background and which are part of the foreground.

For example, a higher threshold might be more conservative, considering only pixels that are confidently background, while a lower threshold might be more inclusive, potentially including more pixels in the background region.

nodes.title: Alpha_Matting_Erode_size Info
widgets_values:
determines the size of the structuring element used in the erosion step of an alpha matting process. Adjusting this parameter might impact how much the foreground region is eroded, influencing the accuracy of the alpha matting result.

For example, a larger erode size might result in more aggressive erosion, potentially removing more of the foreground, while a smaller erode size might be less aggressive. The choice of the appropriate erode size depends on the characteristics of the images you are working with and the desired level of detail preservation in the alpha matting process.
